Difficult to say whether certain things are true of "a robot" when it comes to both behavior and ability, given that, within the limits of available technology, whether a robot can do something is up to the hardware and software given to it. Like, can "a robot" communicate, or sense smells, or even "tell right from wrong"? I would say we have the *technology* to make a robot sense smells perfectly, communicate reasonably, and arguably to a degree tell right from wrong, but you could very easily make "a robot" that doesn't do any of those things at all... beetles are defined by their species, but robots are defined by how they're made, not what they do.

I was unclear about the nature of the robot: was it a toy robot, an advanced existing robot, or something else (e.g., a hypothetical future robot with human-like qualities)? Based on the not very human-like photo of the robot shown, I went with "existing advanced robot," although I might not have been wholly consistent. Perhaps it might be worth explicitly asking research participants something along the lines, "Were you thinking of a robot that was: a toy; an existing robot; a robot that might exist in 20 years; something else?" /  / It might also be interesting to ask something about the educational backgrounds of participants. My hypothesis (perhaps irrelevant to this study) would be that level of education would have a significant influence on responses.
